   {:e #blake3 "1f549a76e0056c98c6e451d188875121ac0ceba142043e824e6dec4e7b2943a9" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :task/t-60982fa8; Session entity: :recon/trace-49aef64f7bb808e4; Session entity: :task/t-59f58258; GENESIS-9: SURPRISE-WEIGHTED CONCEPT CENTROIDS — the saw-tooth invariant as a mechanism. INSIGHT CHAIN: (1) Piaget's grasping mechanism = our hypothesis mechanism. Child grasps water and fails → schema restructures. Agent predicts ΔF(S) and is wrong → hypothesis falsified. (2) Piaget's disequilibrium = hypothesis falsification. The magnitude of the schema violation = the magnitude of the prediction error. (3) Surprise IS the information-theoretic quantity that measures how much an observation violates the current model. Shannon: information content = negative log probability = surprise. A confirming observation adds ~0 bits. A surprising observation adds many bits. (4) The hypothesis ledger already measures this: predicted ΔF(S) vs actual ΔF(S). The difference is prediction error = surprise. The saw-tooth invariant (ADR-FOUNDATION-020) says healthy F(S) oscillates: dips from falsification (surprise), recovery to higher peaks (accommodation). Monotonic increase = echo chamber. (5) UNIFICATION: Piaget (disequilibrium magnitude), Popper (falsification strength), Shannon (information content), and the hypothesis ledger (prediction error) are ALL THE SAME QUANTITY: surprise. It was always one thing. THE CONCRETE FIX: Surprise-weighted concept centroids. Current CCE-2 design: centroid = running mean of member embeddings, every observation contributes equally. This is WRONG. The observation that surprises the concept carries MORE INFORMATION than the one that confirms. Shannon proved this. The fix: weight each observation's contribution to the centroid by its surprise at join time. surprise_i = 1.0 - cosine(observation_i, centroid_at_time_of_joining). weight_i = 1.0 + alpha * surprise_i. new_centroid = sum(weight_i * embedding_i) / sum(weight_i). An observation that confirms (cosine=1.0, surprise=0.0) contributes weight 1.0. An observation at the join threshold (cosine=0.65, surprise=0.35) contributes weight ~1.35. The centroid PULLS TOWARD THE SURPRISING DIRECTION — toward the frontier of the concept, not its interior. This is the centroid analog of the UCB exploration bonus. The concept learns its own boundary from surprise. The boundary IS the most informative part — where concepts meet, where interesting questions live, where steering vectors should point. IMPLEMENTATION: Store :exploration/surprise (cosine distance at join time) as a datom. Use it as weight in centroid computation. One formula change in CCE-2's update_centroid(). COMPOUNDS WITH: surprise-weighted centroids → better boundaries → better matching → better steering questions → more surprising observations → faster convergence. The saw-tooth becomes a mechanism, not just a metric." :op :assert}
